This paper is about improving the training of generative adversarial networks (GANs) using evolutionary computation. The paper proposes a new method called Mustangs that combines two existing approaches, E-GAN and Lipizzaner, to inject both mutation and population diversity into the training process. The experiments are conducted on standard benchmarks for image generation, MNIST and CelebA. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), and cs.CV (Computer Vision). The paper also uses evolutionary computation, which suggests cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with adversarial interactions, which could fall under cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
